[CONTEXT] M. O. Koshy's The Dutch Power in Kerala mentions this place: "The island [of Dharmapattanam] was of strategic importance to the English since 'it is a Lock or Bar to the Rivers of Trintapatam, Bengatt Durmapatam and Codolee [...].'" Based on Google Maps, these 3 rivers might be: Anjarakandy River (Ancharakkandi Puzha - GeoNames ID 8441801); Ummanchira River; Kuyyali River.. Source: " M. O. Koshy, The Dutch Power in Kerala, 1729-1758", p. 134

[RELATION: Part Of Kodungallur (Kingdom) ()] Challij is indicated on the map as being part of "the land of the Samoryn or the kingdom of Krangenoor (Kodungallur)." This suggests that the kingdom of Krangenoor was conquered by the Samoryn (Zamorin or Samuthiri) or the King of Calicut. The map also demarcates the Kingdom of Calicut as being separate from the Kingdom of Kodungallur.

[CONTEXT] In the GLOBALISE dataset, the islands of Muttu and Kunnu are treated as 2 separate entries (GLOB_910 and GLOB_911), because VOC documents referred to them as 2 islands. On the map, however, draws them as one island, with a merged name (Mottoekoene). In present day no islands of these names exist, but there is the populated place at the same location named Mutakunnu or Moothakunnam..
